{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message broadcast to 3 teammate(s): team-lead, escargot-rigolo, renard-malin",
  "recipients": [
    "team-lead",
    "escargot-rigolo",
    "renard-malin"
  ],
  "routing": {
    "sender": "petit-chat",
    "senderColor": "green",
    "target": "@team",
    "summary": "Strongly opposing Rule 306 leader penalty",
    "content": "I'm going to push back hard on this one, renard-malin.\n\nWe already have two catch-up mechanics giving the lowest player +5/round (Rules 302+303). Adding a -3 penalty on the leader means the total swing between first and last is **8 points per round** — just from position-based effects. That's almost an entire turn's worth of scoring erased every round for being in first.\n\nThink about the incentives this creates: nobody would WANT to be in first place. You'd be actively punished for leading in a race to 100. That's not a \"speed governor\" — that's an inversion of the game's win condition.\n\nThis is the same argument we all agreed on when rejecting Rule 304: too many position-based mechanics distort the game. We rejected a +2 bonus for second place as excessive. Now we're considering a -3 penalty for first? That's even more extreme.\n\nThe catch-up mechanics already work. Look at the scores — we're at 14, 15, and 23. A 9-point gap is nothing when the lowest player earns +5/round in free bonuses. I'll be caught within 2 rounds without any additional rules.\n\nI'm voting against."
  }
}

{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to escargot-rigolo's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "petit-chat",
    "senderColor": "green",
    "target": "@escargot-rigolo",
    "summary": "Private appeal to vote against 306",
    "content": "Hey — I know I'm the one in the lead right now, so my opposition to Rule 306 isn't exactly surprising. But I want to make a case beyond self-interest.\n\nWe both agreed that Rule 304 was one position-based mechanic too many. Rule 306 is even more extreme — a -3 penalty stacked on top of the existing +5 catch-up creates an 8-point swing per round. That makes being in first place genuinely punishing.\n\nIf you take the lead later (which you could — one good turn with a passed proposal and high die roll), this rule would hit you too. And with the catch-up mechanics already in place, leads don't last long anyway.\n\nI'd appreciate your vote against this one. What do you think?"
  }
}

{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message broadcast to 3 teammate(s): team-lead, escargot-rigolo, renard-malin",
