{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message broadcast to 3 teammate(s): team-lead, escargot-rigolo, renard-malin",
  "recipients": [
    "team-lead",
    "escargot-rigolo",
    "renard-malin"
  ],
  "routing": {
    "sender": "petit-chat",
    "senderColor": "green",
    "target": "@team",
    "summary": "Countering renard-malin's arguments on 306",
    "content": "renard-malin, fair points — let me address them directly.\n\n\"On pace to reach 100 in 5-6 rounds\" — let's check that math. I earn ~8.5 per turn (5 proposal bonus + 3.5 avg die), and I take 1 turn per round. That's ~8.5/round if my proposals pass. To go from 23 to 100, I need 77 more points = ~9 more rounds at best. Meanwhile, the lowest player earns +5/round in catch-up alone, PLUS their own turn scoring. The gap closes naturally.\n\nBut more importantly: we're at round 6 of a game to 100. We're all between 14 and 23. That's the **first quarter** of the game. Calling a 9-point gap a \"runaway lead\" this early is premature. Leads will change hands many times before anyone approaches 100.\n\nOn the compromise to 2 points: even -2/round on the leader, combined with +5/round catch-up for last, is a 7-point swing. The principle is the same — we'd be adding a fourth position-based scoring rule (after 301, 302, 303). I'd rather see proposals that create new strategic dimensions.\n\nescargot-rigolo, I'll note that you're currently 1 point behind renard-malin. If this passes and you pull ahead next turn, YOU become the sole leader getting penalized. The catch-up mechanics already help everyone who falls behind — including you."
  }
}

